HeatMap

a great way to visualize the abundance of metabolites across different samples. They can provide an overview of the data and help identify patterns or clusters of metabolites that are co-regulated or have similar profiles across conditions

#copy the original data 
data_heatmap <- plasma
#change rownaames 
rownames(data_heatmap)<-plasma$`QMDiab-ID`
#extract the T2D column values for using in the annotation of heatmap while 0 -> N and 1-> Y
T2D <- data.frame( T2D = ifelse(grepl("1",data_heatmap$T2D),
                                    "Y","N"),
                     row.names = row.names(data_heatmap))

#select the whole data set except the clinical data 
data_heatmap <- data_heatmap[,-c(1 ,c(501:507))]

Normality check using shapiro test for chossing Appropriate correlation method

#calculate the mean for each metabolite 
means <- data.frame(apply(data_heatmap, 1, mean))
#shapiro test 
shapiro.test(means$apply.data_heatmap..1..mean.)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  means$apply.data_heatmap..1..mean.
## W = 0.99497, p-value = 0.3007

the data are parametric because of p_value is greater than 0.05

pheatmap(as.matrix(data_heatmap)  , 
         scale = "column", 
         clustering_distance_rows = "correlation", #using pearson correlation for parametric data 
         clustering_distance_cols = "correlation" , 
         clustering_method = "ward.D", #to minimize the variance between clusters 
         fontsize = 15,  color =  rev(colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(11, "RdGy"))(256)),

linear regression

#copy the daataframe  
plasma_reg <- plasma
#make the samples as rownames for easy to use 
rownames(plasma_reg)<-plasma_reg$`QMDiab-ID`
#delete the sample ids column 
plasma_reg<- plasma_reg[,-c(1)]
#empty vector to store the p-values 
p_values <-rep(NA, ncol(plasma_reg[,-c(501:507)]))

#loop over each metabolite and use it in the linear regression model fromula 
#And extract the p-value for T2D for each metabolites 
# store it in the p-value vector 
for(i in 1:ncol(plasma_reg[,-c(501:507)])){
  met <- plasma_reg[,i]

  model <- lm(met ~ T2D + AGE + GENDER + BMI 
            , data =plasma_reg ) 
  p_values[i] <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]

}

significant metabolities

#create new data frame and adding p-values 
significants <-cbind(data.frame(t(plasma_reg[,-c(501:507)])) , p_values) 
#select p-values with metabolites in rownames 
significants_pvalue <- significants %>% dplyr::select(p_values)

Scatter plot for significant metabolities

#add color column to determine the significant metabolities in the whole data set 
significants_pvalue$color <- ifelse(significants_pvalue$p_values < 0.05 , "Significant", "NON")


ggplot(significants_pvalue , aes(y = p_values , x = rownames(significants_pvalue), colour = color)) + 
   geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.7) + 
  theme(legend.background = element_rect( linetype="solid",colour ="black")) + 
  theme( axis.line.y = element_line(colour = "black",linetype = "solid")) +
  theme(legend.position="top" , legend.title=element_blank()) +
  theme(text=element_text(size=16, face = "bold")) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#5D6D7E","#D11300" )) + 
  theme(  panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "white")) + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "") +
  geom_hline(yintercept= 0.05, size=1.5, linetype="dashed", alpha=0.7) +
  xlab("Metabolites") +
  ylab("P_value_squared") + scale_y_sqrt() #for maximize scale of the data

Biological insights

What are those Metabolites ?

For example, 1,5-anhydroglucitol (1,5-AG) is a marker of short-term glycemic control and has been shown to be lower in people with diabetes, indicating a potential role in the pathogenesis of the disease. Similarly, changes in the metabolism of fatty acids and their derivatives, such as 1,2-dipalmitoylglycerol and 1-oleoylglycerophosphocholine, have been linked to insulin resistance and impaired glucose metabolism, which are key features of type 2 diabetes.

Other metabolites on the list may have more indirect associations with type 2 diabetes, such as 3-indoxyl sulfate, which is produced by gut bacteria and has been linked to insulin resistance and inflammation. Additionally, some metabolites on the list may be related to secondary complications of diabetes, such as 4-hydroxyhippurate, which has been associated with diabetic nephropathy.

What does that tell us about type 2 diabetes?

Fatty acids and their metabolites, such as diacylglycerol, have been shown to contribute to insulin resistance and impaired glucose metabolism, which are key features of type 2 diabetes. Elevated levels of ketone bodies have also been linked to insulin resistance and impaired glucose metabolism, as well as increased inflammation and oxidative stress, which can further contribute to the development of type 2 diabetes.

Changes in glycolysis, gluconeogenesis, and pyruvate metabolism have also been observed in people with type 2 diabetes. These metabolic pathways are involved in the production and breakdown of glucose, and alterations in their activity can lead to hyperglycemia and impaired glucose tolerance.

Xanthine metabolism has been implicated in the development of oxidative stress, which can damage cells and tissues and contribute to the development of diabetes-related complications. Lysolipids, which are produced from the hydrolysis of phospholipids, have been shown to be elevated in people with insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes.

Changes in amino acid metabolism, including the metabolism of phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan, have also been observed in people with type 2 diabetes. These changes can contribute to insulin resistance and impair glucose metabolism.
